body: As stated in another [issue](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/issues/2404#issuecomment-554593653), have you ruled out the fact that your input is already on the GPU (```    input_tensor = input_tensor.cuda()```)?

@pranavsharma 

I have used [inference_session_test.cc](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/master/onnxruntime/test/framework/inference_session_test.cc) to test my model, input and output are already on the GPU. Forward takes `378us`, which is similar with python demo (390us).

    1: [ RUN      ] InferenceSessionTests.TestIssue2434
    1: Elapsed time in microseconds : 378 µs
    1: Elapsed time in milliseconds : 0 ms

If remove the `topk` operator from model, forward only takes `26us`. 

    1: [ RUN      ] InferenceSessionTests.TestIssue2434
    1: Elapsed time in microseconds : 26 µs
    1: Elapsed time in milliseconds : 0 ms
Pytorch' `topk` only takes about 24us in this case.

How did you establish that all nodes were on GPU? There was no CUDA implementation of TopK in v1 of ONNX Runtime. It was added November 1, and with that I see a different issue that causes it to fail (looking into that, but it's a memory issue not performance once).

I tested this model with python api, and set `onnxruntime.set_default_logger_severity(0)`, output log as below:
```
2019-12-02 09:27:02.221911922 [V:onnxruntime:, inference_session.cc:442 TransformGraph] Node placements
2019-12-02 09:27:02.221916684 [V:onnxruntime:, inference_session.cc:444 TransformGraph] All nodes have been placed on [CUDAExecutionProvider].
2019-12-02 09:27:02.221946426 [I:onnxruntime:, session_state.cc:22 SetGraph] SaveMLValueNameIndexMapping
2019-12-02 09:27:02.221955692 [I:onnxruntime:, session_state.cc:67 SetGraph] Done saving OrtValue mappings.
```
It shows that all nodes have been placed on GPU.

https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/pull/2523 will address the memory issue. Not sure if it will have a significant impact on performance.

The current TopK implementation does a full sort of the data. Something like https://github.com/facebook/fbcuda/blob/master/TopK.cuh could be considered. @RandySheriffH 

https://github.com/anilshanbhag/gpu-topk has some additional options but doesn't support key-value yet.

The fix helps with perf already by trimming off cuda threads:
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/48490400/70094290-143e4a80-15d7-11ea-9807-2a86529232e2.png)
I am with GTX 1050 Ti. @TianzhongSong , would u mind try on your end?
Hi, i have tried again, but the speed of `topk` has no change.

Implementing http://anilshanbhag.in/static/papers/gputopk_sigmod18.pdf
Prototype done - https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/tree/rashuai/BoostTopK
Refactoring with more tests.
@RandySheriffH Awesome job, speed of `topk` has been greatly improved. Thank you.

@RandySheriffH 

Returns wrong results when the size of the given dimension is too large.

Pytorch script:

    import torch
    import torch.nn as nn
    import numpy as np

    class Model(nn.Module):
        def __init__(self, k=3):
            super(Model, self).__init__()
            self.k = k

        def forward(self, x):
            v, ind = x.topk(self.k, dim=1)
            return v, ind

    model = Model()

    data = np.zeros((1, 1000), dtype=np.float32)
    data[0, 0:6] = np.array([0.1, 0.3, 0.02, 0.45, 0.08, 0.05])
    data = torch.from_numpy(data)

    score, index = model(data)
    print(score)
    print(index)

    torch.onnx.export(model, data, "topk.onnx",
                      opset_version=11,
                      verbose=False,
                      input_names=['data'],
                      output_names=['score', 'index'],
                      dynamic_axes={'data': {0: 'batch', 1: 'channel'},
                                    'score': {0: 'batch', 1: 'channel'},
                                    'index': {0: 'batch', 1: 'channel'}})

onnxruntime script:

    import onnxruntime as ort
    import numpy as np

    print(ort.get_device())

    model = 'topk.onnx'

    sess = ort.InferenceSession(model)

    data = np.zeros((1, 1000), dtype=np.float32)
    data[:, 0:6] = np.array([0.1, 0.3, 0.02, 0.45, 0.08, 0.05])

    inputs = {'data': data}

    score, index = sess.run(['score', 'index'], inputs)
    print(score)
    print(index)

Pytorch output:
    tensor([[0.4500, 0.3000, 0.1000]])
    tensor([[3, 1, 0]])

ORT output:
    [[0. 0. 0.]]
    [[0 0 0]]

Now, changing the size of dimension 1: `data = np.zeros((1, 500), dtype=np.float32)`, ORT output as below:
[[0.45 0.3  0.1 ]]
[[3 1 0]]

issue.title: onnxruntime model slower on gpu than pytorch implementation

repository.name: onnxruntime
repository.description: ONNX Runtime: cross-platform, high performance ML inferencing and training accelerator

issue.body:
**Describe the bug**
After exporting a model from pytorch to onnx I observed that the runtimes on the GPU are much slower for the onnx model even after a couple of forward passes as the first one is usually very slow. The times are:
- onnx gpu: 0.5579626560211182 s
- onnx cpu: 1.3775670528411865 s
- pytorch gpu: 0.008594512939453125 s
- pytorch cpu: 2.582857370376587 s

All nodes seems to be placed on the GPU as you can see from the output when setting the logger level to 0 (full output at the end) but there is still some indication that the cpu is used:
```
[V:onnxruntime:, inference_session.cc:639 TransformGraph] All nodes have been placed on [CUDAExecutionProvider].
...
[I:onnxruntime:Default, bfc_arena.cc:238 AllocateRawInternal] Extending BFCArena for Cpu. bin_num:14 rounded_bytes:6684672
```
I was not able to find a single function which is the bottleneck as it was the case in [#2434](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/issues/2434).

**System information**
- OS Platform and Distribution: Ubuntu 18.04
- ONNX Runtime installed from: Source with CUDA support
- ONNX Runtime version: 1.2.0
- Python version: 3.6.9
- PyTorch version: 1.5.0
- GCC/Compiler version: 7.5.0
- CUDA/cuDNN version: 10.2/7.6.5
- GPU model and memory: Quadro M500M, 2GB

**To Reproduce**
The final implementation will be in C++ but for easier testing I share a python script where I can observe the same issues:

```
import numpy as np
import onnx
import onnxruntime as ort
import time
import torch
import torch.nn as nn

class Model(nn.Module):
    def __init__(self):
        super(Model, self).__init__()

        self.encoder_1 = self.generate_encoder()
        self.encoder_2 = self.generate_encoder()

        # detector head
        self.detector_head_convolutions = [
            nn.ReflectionPad2d(1),
            nn.Conv2d(128, 256, 3),
            *self.getNonlinearity(256),
            nn.Conv2d(256, 65, 1),
            nn.BatchNorm2d(65)
        ]

        self.detector_head_convolutions = nn.Sequential(*self.detector_head_convolutions)

        self.softmax = nn.Softmax2d()
        self.shuffle = nn.PixelShuffle(8)

        self.descriptor_head_convolutions = [
            nn.ReflectionPad2d(1),
            nn.Conv2d(128, 256, 3),
            *self.getNonlinearity(256),
            nn.Conv2d(256, 256, 1),
            nn.BatchNorm2d(256)
        ]

        self.descriptor_head_convolutions = nn.Sequential(*self.descriptor_head_convolutions)

    def forward(self, image_1, image_2):
        x1 = self.encoder_1(image_1)
        x2 = self.encoder_2(image_2)

        return self.detector_head(x1), self.detector_head(x2), self.descriptor_head(x1), self.descriptor_head(x2)

    def getNonlinearity(self, N):
        return nn.BatchNorm2d(N), nn.ReLU(True)

    def detector_head(self, x):
        logits = self.detector_head_convolutions(x)

        prob = self.softmax(logits)
        prob = self.shuffle(prob[:,:-1])
        return prob

    def descriptor_head(self, x):
        x = self.descriptor_head_convolutions(x)
        x = torch.nn.functional.normalize(x, p=2, dim=1)
        return x

    def generate_encoder(self):
        encoder = nn.Sequential(
            nn.ReflectionPad2d(1),
            nn.Conv2d(1, 64, 3),
            *self.getNonlinearity(64),

            nn.ReflectionPad2d(1),
            nn.Conv2d(64, 64, 3),
            *self.getNonlinearity(64),

            nn.MaxPool2d(2,2),

            nn.ReflectionPad2d(1),
            nn.Conv2d(64, 64, 3),
            *self.getNonlinearity(64),

            nn.ReflectionPad2d(1),
            nn.Conv2d(64, 64, 3),
            *self.getNonlinearity(64),

            nn.MaxPool2d(2,2),

            nn.ReflectionPad2d(1),
            nn.Conv2d(64, 128, 3),
            *self.getNonlinearity(128),

            nn.ReflectionPad2d(1),
            nn.Conv2d(128, 128, 3),
            *self.getNonlinearity(128),

            nn.MaxPool2d(2,2),

            nn.ReflectionPad2d(1),
            nn.Conv2d(128, 128, 3),
            *self.getNonlinearity(128),

            nn.ReflectionPad2d(1),
            nn.Conv2d(128, 128, 3),
            *self.getNonlinearity(128),
        )

        return encoder

if __name__ == '__main__':
    net = Model()
    net.eval()

    # dummy inputs with the correct image sizes
    img1 = torch.rand([1,1,512,816])
    img2 = torch.rand([1,1,512,640])
    img1_np = img1.numpy()
    img2_np = img2.numpy()

    # one forward pass to double check the exported model
    p_1, p_2, d_1, d_2 = net(img1, img2)

    # Export the model
    torch.onnx.export(net,
                      (img1, img2),
                      'test.onnx',
                      export_params=True,
                      opset_version=10,
                      do_constant_folding=True,
                      input_names = ['img1', 'img2'],
                      output_names = ['prob_1', 'prob_2', 'desc_1', 'desc_2'])

    # check the model
    onnx_model = onnx.load('test.onnx')
    onnx.checker.check_model(onnx_model)

    # check prediction of onnx model
    import onnxruntime as ort
    
#     ort.set_default_logger_severity(0)

    # Set graph optimization level
    sess_options = ort.SessionOptions()
    sess_options.graph_optimization_level = ort.GraphOptimizationLevel.ORT_ENABLE_EXTENDED

    ort_sess = ort.InferenceSession('test.onnx', sess_options)

    outputs = ort_sess.run(None, {'img1': img1_np,
                                  'img2': img2_np})

    np.testing.assert_allclose(p_1.detach().numpy(), outputs[0], rtol=1e-03, atol=1e-05)
    np.testing.assert_allclose(p_2.detach().numpy(), outputs[1], rtol=1e-03, atol=1e-05)
    np.testing.assert_allclose(d_1.detach().numpy(), outputs[2], rtol=1e-03, atol=1e-05)
    np.testing.assert_allclose(d_2.detach().numpy(), outputs[3], rtol=1e-03, atol=1e-05)

    print("Exported model has been tested with ONNXRuntime, and the result looks good!")
    
    with torch.no_grad():
        # profiling
        t_start = time.time()
        outputs = ort_sess.run(None, {'img1': img1_np,
                                      'img2': img2_np})
        print('onnx time all providers: ' + str(time.time() - t_start))
        print('providers: ', ort_sess.get_providers())
 
        ort_sess.set_providers(['CPUExecutionProvider'])
        t_start = time.time()
        outputs = ort_sess.run(None, {'img1': img1_np,
                                      'img2': img2_np})
        print('onnx time cpu only: ' + str(time.time() - t_start))

        del ort_sess # free gpu memory

        t_start = time.time()
        p_o, p_t, d_o, d_t = net(img1, img2)
        print('pytorch time cpu: ' + str(time.time() - t_start))

        if torch.cuda.is_available():
            net = net.cuda()
            t_start = time.time()
            p_o, p_t, d_o, d_t = net(img1.cuda(), img2.cuda())
            print('pytorch time gpu: ' + str(time.time() - t_start))
```



**Expected behavior**
The onnx model on the GPU should have faster or equal inference times than the pytorch implementation.

**Screenshots**
This is the output if I run 
```
2020-05-07 16:26:29.723769555 [I:onnxruntime:Default, bfc_arena.cc:14 BFCArena] Creating BFCArena for Cuda
```
